## 9. Interview Points
- `private` fields are accessed using **getters and setters** (Encapsulation).
- A top-level class cannot be `private` or `protected`.
- `protected` is mainly used in **inheritance** across packages.
- Default access is also called **package-private**.
- Access modifiers apply to classes, fields, methods, and constructors.

---

## 10. Common Mistakes
| Mistake | Correct Way |
|---|---|
| Accessing `private` field directly from outside class | Use getter/setter methods |
| Marking top-level class as `private` | Top-level class can only be `public` or default |
| Confusing `default` with `protected` | Default = same package only; Protected = same package + subclasses |

---

## 11. Difference Table

| Modifier | Keyword Written | Scope |
|---|---|---|
| Public | `public` | Everywhere |
| Protected | `protected` | Same package + subclasses |
| Default | *(nothing)* | Same package only |
| Private | `private` | Same class only |

---

## 12. Memory Trick
> **"P-P-D-Pu" тЖТ Private, Protected, Default, Public**
> Think of it as **doors with locks**:
> ЁЯФТЁЯФТЁЯФТ Private тЖТ only you have the key
> ЁЯФТЁЯФТ Protected тЖТ family has the key
> ЁЯФТ Default тЖТ colony has the key
> ЁЯЪк Public тЖТ no lock, open for all